Elon Musk is forced to leave the post of head of the board of directors of Tesla
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and Tesla founder Elon Musk settled their dispute over the fraud case.
This is reported by CNBC News.
According to the channel, as part of the agreements, Musk will have to leave the post of head of the board of directors of Tesla.
At the same time, the commission allowed Musk to retain the post of head of Tesla.
As noted, the founder of Tesla will also have to pay an administrative fine of $ 20 million.
A similar amount will be charged to Tesla.
The money will be distributed among the affected investors.
In addition, the company must appoint two independent directors.
Elon Musk is an American entrepreneur, included in the list of the 50 richest people on the planet according to Forbes magazine.
He is the head of the SpaceX space corporation, the neurotech company Neuralink and the developer of Tesla electric cars, as well as the co-founder of Paypal.
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission has previously sued Tesla CEO Elon Musk over his tweet about a possible buyout of the company.
Last month, Musk announced plans to make Tesla a private company and buy back all shares on the exchange at a fixed price of $420.
The price of $420 was allegedly set “because of the importance of this number in the culture of marijuana,” Bloomberg reported earlier, citing the co-director of the security department of the Commission Stephen Peikin.
At the same time, Elon Musk subsequently abandoned his plans to buy back shares.
Commenting on the lawsuit filed against him by the US Securities and Exchange Commission, the businessman said that he considers the allegations of fraud unfounded, and added that he was very disappointed and saddened by these claims.
“Honesty is the most important value in my life, and the facts will prove that I did not violate it in any way,” the businessman said in an interview with CNBC.
At the same time, in August, a group of Tesla shareholders filed a class action lawsuit against Musk, complaining about the financial losses incurred.
The plaintiffs claimed that the posts of the businessman brought them losses.
In particular, one of the shareholders said that the businessman’s tweets were misleading, because of which sellers of Tesla shares were forced to buy securities at artificially inflated prices to cover their positions.
Also, other plaintiffs noted that the careless statements of Elon Musk led to sharp fluctuations in the course.
In September, Ilona Mask accused the head of the research company Citron Research of stock market fraud.
Meanwhile, if Musk could not settle his dispute with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, he would face removal from the management of the company and even prison.
This was stated by the former chairman of the Commission Harvey Pitt.
Musk is “a good guy who can’t run a car company.”
