By the way, the release of penicillin from mold mushrooms was not Fleming’s first discovery.
A few years earlier, when he had a cold, he sown mucus from his own nose on a petri dish (this is a glass lid in which experiments with bacteria are conducted) and a few days later found that the bacteria that were there were destroyed.
In the same way, penicillin was also discovered.
Fleming’s name was included in the list of the 100 most outstanding personalities in the history of mankind.
His discovery, according to many scientists, changed the course of history.
With the help of penicillin, medicine began to cope with most of the oldest diseases that were previously considered incurable - tuberculosis, syphilis, gangrene ...
When, shortly after receiving the Nobel Prize, Fleming arrived in the French capital in 1945, Parisian newspapers wrote: “To defeat fascism and liberate France, he did more than dozens of divisions.”
According to experts, Fleming’s discovery of the world’s first antibiotic saved the lives of more than 200 million people on Earth.
Alexander Fleming died at his home in London in 1955 of a heart attack.
He was cremated, and a week later his ashes were buried in the famous St. Paul's Cathedral in London.
