Kosachev: At the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly, the topic of Russia in a negative way was practically absent
The head of the Federation Council Committee on Foreign Affairs Konstantin Kosachev considers the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly successful for Russia and does not exclude that it can become a turning point in the perception of the Russian Federation as an integral participant in solving global problems.
“The uniqueness of the current 73rd session, in my opinion, is that the rhetoric, to which we are already almost accustomed in recent years in relation to Russia, was now an order of magnitude more muted,” the senator said in an interview published on Sunday by the Russian newspaper.
He explained that in previous years, the Russian Federation was sometimes “designated as one of the three main threats to humanity, then along with Ebola, then along with climate change or terrorism, Russia was in this row, at least in the statement of a group of Western countries, which expressed itself in this regard quite unanimously.”
At the 73rd session, Kosachev stressed, “Russia’s topic in a negative way was practically absent.”
“If you carefully analyze the speech of the President of the United States, the President of France, the speech of the Minister of foreign Affairs of Germany, I do not take Ukraine, Georgia, or the British, in any case, the choir was not exactly”, — said the politician, noting that Russia “was no longer some kind of wall, which trains strikes with a tennis ball.”
The head of the profile committee of the Federation Council does not exclude that this indicates a certain trend, which, in his opinion, “will highlight the current session [of the UN General Assembly], although this trend may fully manifest itself in a year, two, three.”
“I do not exclude that the current session in some sense can be a turning point,” Kosachev admitted, explaining that “too many examples of how Russia’s involvement manages to move forward in international affairs.”
As an example, he cited the situation in Syria, around Iran and North Korea.
“Unfortunately, this is not Ukraine, but I have no doubt that the Russian vision of the Ukrainian crisis will also be in demand over time,” the MP added.
This is due to the fact that there is an adequate, healthy perception of Russia as not just a possible - an integral participant in solving global problems of our time.
“I wouldn’t like to be wrong, but I have the feeling that we are somewhere passing a point beyond which the movement will no longer be a movement backward, it will be a movement forward,” he added.
Another “interesting and important feeling” in this context, Kosachev called “a request for a Russian vision of how the modern world should develop.”
“I attended many meetings of the head of the Russian delegation [at the session of the General Assembly], Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov, I held my own meetings, and I saw with great pleasure that if a year or two or five years ago the Russian opinion, the Russian vision of what is happening in the world, by and large, no one was interested, now the situation is different,” he said.
According to him, this is due to the fact that the so-called new liberal order, which is personified with the West, has no answers to the questions of how to solve world problems due to the obvious lack of ideas in the global space, a lack of ideas on how to solve the problems of the Middle East, the problems of terrorism, the problems of nuclear non-proliferation, the problems of migration.
“And here the request for the Russian vision is becoming more and more obvious,” Kosachev said, stressing that he believes in this sense “the current session is good for the work of the Russian delegation, good for Russia.”
