EU allocates 1.5 million euros to help victims in Indonesia
The European Union (EU) has provided Indonesia with 1.5 million euros to combat the effects of the earthquake and tsunami.
This was reported on September 30 by the press service of the European Commission.
In order to monitor the provision of assistance, the European Commission sent its experts to the region.
As noted, the funds will be used for disinfection, as well as providing the victims with food, water, temporary shelters and medicines.
The Commission also granted Indonesian authorities access to European Emergency Service satellite maps of Copernicus to assess the damage.
The United States also expressed readiness to assist in the aftermath of the disaster, said in a statement the head of the press service of the US State Department Heather Nauert.
It is also reported that the US diplomatic mission in Indonesia has not received reports of injured American citizens.
